  "answer": "In *The Wanderer*, the speaker (often called the Wanderer or earth-stepper) introduces Wyrd early as \"wholly steadfast,\" framing it as an inexorable, autonomous force that governs exile and hardship beyond human control or mitigation.[^1] This portrays Wyrd with full causal agency over life's vicissitudes—slaughter, loss, decay—such that even a \"weary mind cannot withstand [it],\" and it acts alongside weapons or storms as a co-agent in destruction.[^2] The Wanderer's resignation concedes near-total *external* determinism: human agency is marginal, reduced to endurance, lamentation, or seeking divine mercy from the \"Measurer\" or \"Father in heaven,\" with no implication that prior choices shape Wyrd's decree.[^3]\n\nBy contrast, Manusmṛti Book 12 attributes all causation to *karmic* agency rooted in the individual's own actions (\"karma\"): \"Action, which springs from the mind, speech, and body, has good and bad results; the states of men, high, low, and middle, are born of their karma.\" Outcomes like rebirths, prosperity, or torment arise mechanistically from one's ethical choices (e.g., violence yields animal births; theft, vermin), preserving robust human moral agency while binding future states to past deeds.[^4] Penances can even mitigate karma, underscoring controllability absent in Wyrd.[^5]\n\nSuperficially, both evoke resignation to an inevitable cosmic order (Wyrd's \"decree of the Fates\"; karma's unerring fruition). Yet the Wanderer's fatalism is *further* from Manu's account than appears: Wyrd disempowers humans as passive recipients of an opaque, steadfast fate, whereas karma *empowers* agency as self-wrought causation, demanding ethical action for better outcomes. The Christian undertones in *The Wanderer* (grace from God) introduce transcendent hope but do not retroactively grant humans control over Wyrd itself.\n\n[^1]: *Old English Elegies*, \"The Wanderer\" [paragraph](/works/unknown-old-english-elegies-d5fe9e/11-the-wanderer/translation/#p-9cca5e).\n\n[^2]: *Old English Elegies*, \"The Wanderer\" [paragraph](/works/unknown-old-english-elegies-d5fe9e/11-the-wanderer/translation/#p-9462cc).\n\n[^3]: *Old English Elegies*, \"The Wanderer\" [paragraph](/works/unknown-old-english-elegies-d5fe9e/11-the-wanderer/translation/#p-5bdc65).\n\n[^4]: *Manusmṛti*, Chapter 12 [paragraph](/works/unknown-manusmrti-347b76/12/translation/#p-whatever-for-Mn_12.3); cf. full chapter on karmic states and guṇas.[^6]\n\n[^5]: *Manusmṛti*, Chapter 12 [paragraph](/works/unknown-manusmrti-347b76/12/translation/#p-whatever-for-Mn_12.226) (\"By confession, by remorse, by tapas, and by study, a sinner is freed from sin\").\n\n[^6]: *Manusmṛti*, Chapter 12 [chapter](/works/unknown-manusmrti-347b76/12/translation/).",
